    "source": "inconnu_1779",
    "contenu": "## Document Summary\n\n**Title:** SEEDS\n\n### Cooking Seeds\n\n**Main Points:**\n- **Nature of Seeds:** Seeds are typically dry and hard, requiring more elaborate cooking methods to become edible.\n- **Nutritional Aspects:** Some seeds, like nuts, are high in oils; grains are more starchy. Hot water can help soften seeds by dissolving and relocating carbohydrates and starches, thereby making the nutrients more digestible.\n- **Cooking Techniques:**\n  - **Soaking:** Milling or cutting seeds into smaller pieces removes outer coats, reducing cooking time. Soaking seeds reduces cooking times significantly.\n  - **Heating:** Faster penetration of heat into seeds reduces cooking time even further than water alone.\n\n### Sprouts\n\n**Main Points:**\n- **Benefits of Sprouting:**\n  - Enhances the nutritional content of seeds, particularly in vitamins C and B, iron, and protein.\n  - Transition from dry seed to a sprout offers a midway nutritional value and changes chemically and texturally.\n- **Common usage:** Commonly sprouted seeds include beans and barley. They become sweeter as stored starch is converted into sugars.\n\n### Turning Seeds into Meat Substitutes\n\n**Main Points:**\n- **Use in Vegetarian Cuisine:** Particularly popular among Buddhists in China and Japan.\n- **Methods:** Involves using whole grains, beans, and nuts along with wheat gluten or soybean extract (like seitan and yuba) manipulated to mimic meat textures and flavors.\n\n**Additional Notes:**\n- The text emphasizes how different processing techniques alter cooking times and nutritional availability of seeds in culinary applications, while also offering options for vegetarians to create meat-like dishes from various seeds and their derivatives."
