    "source": "the-wine-bible-karen-macneil.pdf_page_210",
    "contenu": "The document titled \"CONFIRMING THE COLOR\" discusses various aspects of observing and understanding the color of wine, highlighting how it can influence the perception and appreciation of wine. Below are the structured highlights and details covered in the article:\n\n### 1. Importance of Color in Wine Perception\n- **General view**: The color of a wine is often seen as setting up expectations regarding its aromas and flavors.\n- **Author's perspective**: The color is not necessarily linked to aroma or flavor and is considered last in the evaluation process by the author.\n\n### 2. Origin of Wine Color\n- **Source**: Derived from pigments in grape skins known as anthocyanins.\n- **Viewing technique**: Recommends looking down and across a wine-filled glass at a 45-degree angle, rather than directly holding the glass up.\n\n### 3. Varietal Differences in Color\n- Examples of grape varietal colors:\n  - **Pinot noir**: Usually light brick in color.\n  - **Gamay**: Lipstick red.\n  - **Zinfandel and Nebbiolo**: Electric purple to almost black, depending on the specific wine.\n\n### 4. Color as an Indicator\n- **Age relation**: Color can indicate the age of wine; white wines darken as they age, whereas red wines generally lighten.\n  \n### 5. Flavor Intensity Misconception\n- **Common misconception**: Many think the intensity of wine’s color relates directly to the intensity of its flavor.\n- Confirms that deeply red wines (e.g., Cabernet Sauvignon) are not necessarily more flavorful than paler red wines (e.g., Pinot Noir).\n\n### 6. Clarity of Wine\n- **Importance today**: Clarity or limpidity is relevant, with well-made white wines generally having good clarity.\n- **Variability in red wines**: Clarity can vary; some great reds have perfect clarity while others might be more opaque, especially those unfiltered.\n\nThe article emphasizes understanding the nuances of wine color and how it can both influence and mislead in wine tasting and appreciation."
