    "source": "ClassGuide_aout2010-5.pdf_page_112",
    "contenu": "The page from the document titled \"4.4 La vente du vin\" discusses the preparation and content considerations for wine menus. Below is a structured summary of the content captured in several sections and bullet points:\n\n---\n\n### 4.4 La vente du vin\n\n**Cartes et supports de vente:**\n- Mentions obligatoires\n- Mentions facultatives\n\n**Rédaction de la carte des vins:**\n- Importance: Essential for effective product selling and providing clear information to the consumer.\n  \n**Les indications obligatoires:**\nRequired information in the wine list:\n- The exact appellation under which the wine is sold.\n- The container size: bottle, magnum, half-bottle, etc.\n- The net prices including service charge with the indication of the service percentage.\n- The vineyard or \"cru\" identifier.\n\n**Certaines informations facultatives:**\nOptional information that is appreciated includes:\n- Bottling at the château or at the domain, if applicable.\n- The vintage year. The restaurant must sell the bottle of the year mentioned on the card and cannot replace it even in case of stock-outs.\n\n**Common errors in wine menu writing:**\n- Avoid including wines without a designated appellation.\n- List wines precisely under their correct appellation.\n- Specify the appellation in cases of wines sold under a trademarked name because merely having the brand name is not sufficient.\n- Conformity of the seller’s domicile and the appellation. The mention \"controlled appellation\" is often included between the terms \"appellation\" and \"controlled.\"\n- Classify the wines separately and remember to mention the volumetric alcohol content expressed in % (e.g., live including 12.5% vol).\n- For wines served by the glass, if they are not visible on the wine list, they should at least be mentioned on sales supports or displayed in some way.\n\n---\n\nThis critical analysis helps with understanding not only the requirements for a proper wine list but also the common pitfalls to avoid in its creation, ensuring compliance and consumer satisfaction."
  },
