    "source": "359079534-Encyclopedie-de-La-Cuisine-VEGETARIENNE.pdf_page_309",
    "contenu": "### Ingredients for \"Chili sin carne aux deux haricots\"\n\n#### Ingredients\n- 150 g of red kidney beans\n- 150 g of black beans or black-eyed peas\n- 2 carrots (200 g)\n- 2 zucchinis (200 g)\n- 2 to 3 cloves of garlic (20 g)\n- 3 onions (300 g)\n- 1 tablespoon of oil\n- 2 tablespoons of olive oil\n- 1 teaspoon of paprika\n- 1/2 teaspoon ground cumin\n- 1 tablespoon of cider vinegar\n- 60 ml of tomato coulis\n- 15 cl of boiling water\n- 1 bay leaf\n- 2 cloves of garlic\n- 2 pieces of dried oregano\n- 1 chilli pepper\n- 1 small squash (butternut or any kind, depending on personal taste)\n- Cayennne pepper or chili powder, to taste\n- Salt, to taste\n\n#### To Serve\n- 1 bunch of coriander\n- 150 ml of cream fraîche\n- 1 cup grated cheese (e.g., aged cheddar)\n\n#### Technical References\n- Cutting techniques, p. 82\n- Chop onions, p. 39\n- Prepare vegetable broth, p. 31\n- Chop parsley, p. 29\n- Prepare an onion, p. 22\n- Prepare vegetable cream sauce, p. 120\n\n### Recipe: \"Chili sin carne aux deux haricots\"\n\n#### Preparation for 4-6 servings\n- **Preparation Time:** 25 minutes\n- **Cooking Time:** 3 hours (including rest time)\n- **Resting Time:** 8 hours\n\n#### Steps\n1. **Prep Beans:**\n   - Soak the beans for 8 hours. Cook in boiling water for 30 minutes or use a pressure cooker. Check for tenderness and set aside.\n\n2. **Prepare Vegetables:**\n   - Peel and chop onions and carrots into large pieces. Peel garlic and cube pumpkins.\n\n3. **Cook:**\n   - In a large pan, lightly fry the onions, adding celery, carrots, and leek initially. After 5 minutes, add paprika, cumin, simmer for a minute, then add bay leaf, cloves, oregano, tomato coulis, boiling water.\n\n4. **Simmer:**\n   - Add chili, adjust taste with cayenne/chili powder, boil, and reduce to a thick consistency.\n\n5. **Final Steps:**\n   - Place beans in the vegetable mixture, continue cooking for 30 to 45 minutes, allowing the sauce to thicken.\n\n#### Chef's Tips\n- **For a 'Meat-like' Texture:**\n   - You can use 200 g of grainy seitan, chopped finely (ref: technique, p. 69) for a texture similar to hash meat. Hydrate well before use and add to the chili sooner for better integration.\n\n#### Good to Know\n- \"Chili sin carne\" (chili without meat), typical in Mexican cuisine, can be prepared with various chili peppers based on preference, such as habanero, serrano, or jalapeño. Adjust the chili type and hotness according to your taste."
