    "source": "_Brazilian_Fish_and_Shellfish_Stew_Recipe_",
    "contenu": "### Brazilian Fish and Shellfish Stew\n\n#### For Rich, Partly Oak-Aged Viogniers\n**Serves**: 4\n\n#### Ingredients:\n- 1/4 cup white wine\n- 1/4 teaspoon saffron threads, crushed\n- 4 tablespoons (1/2 stick) unsalted butter\n- 2 yellow onions, chopped\n- 2 green bell peppers, seeded and chopped\n- 2 to 3 jalapeño chiles or other hot peppers to taste, finely minced\n- 6 cloves garlic, finely minced\n- 1 tablespoon ground coriander\n- 4 cups Fish Stock (see recipe page 105)\n- 1 1/2 cups drained canned tomatoes, chopped\n- 3 fresh ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded, and diced\n- 1/2 cup canned cream of coconut (such as Coco Lopez), or more to taste\n- 8 tablespoons chopped fresh coriander (cilantro)\n- 2 tablespoons lemon or lime juice, or more to taste\n- Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste\n- 1 1/2 pounds fish fillets (such as monkfish, snapper, rock cod, or flounder), cut into 2-inch pieces\n- 16 manila clams, scrubbed\n- 16 shrimp, peeled and deveined\n- 16 mussels, scrubbed and debearded\n- 16 scallops, foot muscles removed\n- 2 tablespoons toasted coconut (for garnish, optional)\n\n#### Directions:\n1. **Prepare the saffron infusion**: Pour the wine into a small saucepan and bring to a simmer. Remove from heat, add the saffron, and let steep for 10 minutes.\n   \n2. **Cook the vegetables**: In a wide, deep pot, melt the butter over medium heat. Add the onions and cook until translucent, about 8 minutes. Add the bell peppers, jalapeños, garlic, and ground coriander, and sauté until softened and fragrant, about 5 minutes.\n   \n3. **Simmer with tomatoes and stock**: Add the fish stock, canned tomatoes, 1/2 cup of coconut cream, 6 tablespoons of fresh coriander, and the saffron infusion. Simmer to allow the flavors to blend, about 3 minutes.\n   \n4. **Add lemon juice and seasonings**: Stir in 2 tablespoons of lemon or lime juice. Season with salt and pepper. Adjust sweet and sour balance by adding a bit more coconut cream or lemon juice, as needed.\n   \n5. **Cook the seafood**: Add the fish and clams and simmer, covered, for 2 minutes. Then add the shrimp and mussels, discarding any that do not close when tapped with a spoon, and simmer until all seafood is cooked through.\n   \n6. **Garnish and serve**: Optionally garnish with toasted coconut before serving.\n\nThis recipe not only provides a detailed guide on how to prepare a Brazilian Fish and Shellfish Stew but also suggests pairing it with rich, partly oak-aged Viogniers which can complement the flavors of the dish."
  },
