    "contenu": "The document titled \"THE GRAPES OF ARGENTINA\" provides an overview of various white and red grape varieties used in Argentina’s wine production. Here is the organized content:\n\n---\n\n## WHITES\n\n- **CHARDONNAY**: A major grape, especially for exported wines. Wine styles range from simple to toasty and oaky, in the manner of many California chardonnays.\n\n- **TORRONTÉS**: An Argentine specialty, with three distinct varieties: Torrontés Riojana (delightful, dry, spicy, aromatic), Torrontés Sanjuanino (a natural cross of muscat of Alexandria and listán prieto), Torrontés Mendocino (not as aromatic or high in quality, with parentage slightly known as muscat of Alexandria).\n\n---\n\n## REDS\n\n- **BARBERA, SANGIOVESE, AND TEMPRANILLO**: Introduced by early Italian and Spanish immigrants, used mainly in inexpensive blends, sold in jugs or cartons, sometimes as varietal wines.\n\n- **BONARDA**: Formerly Argentina’s main red grape, now second to malbec. Known for its bold, balanced wines that can have some complexity with age. It is a French grape douce noir, called charbono in California.\n\n- **CABERNET SAUVIGNON**: Important for the export market, it offers powerful and sleek wines.\n\n- **CEREZA**: An inexpensive variety used in wines sold in cartons domestically, it’s a cross of listán prieto and muscat of Alexandria.\n\n- **CRIOLLA CHICA**: The same as listán prieto, it's the original grape variety from Spain, brought to Argentina.\n\n- **CRIOLLA GRANDE**: An undistinguished pinkish-skinned grape related to other criollas, used for coarse, bland white and rosé wines.\n\n- **MALBEC**: The most important and impressive red grape in Argentina, originally from Cahors, France. Known for producing wines with gripping, deep, concentrated, and velvety textures.\n\n- **MERLOT**: Although less prestigious and successful compared to cabernet sauvignon, it still offers good value, mostly for the export market.\n\n--- \n\nThis structured information highlights the primary grape types and their attributes in Argentine viticulture."
